ell as political violence and the social underclass. In doing so, he confronts the replication of a colonial and racist geography of reason, allowing theorists from the Global South to emerge as interlocutors alongside northern ones in a move that exemplifies what, Gordon argues, Fanon represented in his plea to establish newer and healthier human relationships beyond colonial paradigms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aIntellectualszAlgeriavBiography. 0aPsychiatristszAlgeriavBiography. 0aRevolutionarieszAlgeriavBiography. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aPostcolonial Studies. 4aRace & Ethnic Studies. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAfricana phenomenology.  aAfricana philosophy.  aBlack political thought.  aExistentialism.  aFrantz Fanon.  aNegritude.  acreolization.  adecolonial thought.  adialectics.  ahumanism.  apostcolonial thought.  arevolutionary thought.1 aCornell, Drucilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornell, Drucilla.1 aDayan-Herzbrun, Sonia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDayan-Herzbrun, Sonia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823266111zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823266111423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823266111/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK